The scalp is composed of five layers, often remembered by the mnemonic SCALP: Skin, Connective tissue, Aponeurosis, Loose areolar tissue, and Periosteum. Superficial injuries generally do not extend beyond the connective tissue layer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin only\u003C/strong\u003E would not account for the involvement of the connective tissue, which is typically affected in superficial wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAponeurosis, loose areolar tissue, periosteum\u003C/strong\u003E are deeper layers of the scalp and are not involved in superficial wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnective tissue only\u003C/strong\u003E would not include the skin, which is also involved in superficial wounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin, connective tissue, and aponeurosis\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a deeper wound that extends beyond the superficial layers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Superficial scalp wounds typically involve the skin and connective tissue layers.","The scalp consists of five layers: skin, connective tissue, aponeurosis, loose areolar tissue, and periosteum.","Understanding the layers of the scalp is important for assessing the depth and severity of scalp injuries."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58512"}},"question":{"data":{"type